module.exports = [
  [119, "Mental Health Awareness", "健康", 2, "Mental health has emerged as one of the most pressing public health challenges of the twenty-first century. The World Health Organization reports that approximately one in eight people globally lives with a mental health condition, yet stigma and inadequate resources prevent many from receiving the care they need.\n\nDepression is the leading cause of disability worldwide, affecting more than 280 million people. Anxiety disorders impact nearly 300 million individuals. These conditions reduce quality of life, impair productivity, and strain relationships. Despite their prevalence, mental health conditions often go untreated, with the treatment gap exceeding 50 percent in many countries.\n\nStigma remains a major barrier to mental health care. Many people view mental illness as a personal weakness rather than a medical condition, discouraging those affected from seeking help. Cultural attitudes vary widely, with some communities viewing mental health problems as shameful or taboo. Anti-stigma campaigns and public education are slowly changing these perceptions.\n\nThe economic impact of mental illness is staggering. Depression and anxiety alone cost the global economy approximately one trillion dollars annually in lost productivity. Investment in mental health services yields significant returns, with every dollar invested in treatment generating four dollars in improved health and productivity. Expanding access to mental health care through telemedicine, community-based services, and integration with primary care can help close the treatment gap.",
"心理健康已成为二十一世纪最紧迫的公共健康挑战之一。世界卫生组织报告全球约八分之一的人患有心理健康问题，但污名和资源不足阻止了许多人获得所需的护理。\n\n抑郁症是全球致残的主要原因，影响超过2.8亿人。焦虑症影响近3亿人。尽管普遍存在，心理健康问题往往得不到治疗。\n\n污名仍然是心理健康护理的主要障碍。许多人将精神疾病视为个人弱点而非医学状况。反污名运动和公众教育正在慢慢改变这些观念。\n\n心理健康的经济影响惊人。仅抑郁症和焦虑症每年就使全球经济损失约1万亿美元的生产力。在心理健康服务方面的投资产生显著回报。",
338, [["What percentage of people globally live with a mental health condition?","About one in twenty","About one in eight","About one in three","About one in two","B","文章指出全球约八分之一的人患有心理健康问题。"],["What is the leading cause of disability worldwide?","Heart disease","Depression","Cancer","Diabetes","B","文章指出抑郁症是全球致残的主要原因。"],["How much do depression and anxiety cost the global economy annually in lost productivity?","About 100 million dollars","About one trillion dollars","About 10 trillion dollars","About one billion dollars","B","文章指出抑郁症和焦虑症每年使全球经济损失约1万亿美元的生产力。"],["What return does every dollar invested in mental health treatment generate?","Two dollars","Four dollars in improved health and productivity","Ten dollars","No return","B","文章指出每投资1美元在治疗上可产生4美元的健康和生产力改善。"]]],

  [120, "Nutrition and Healthy Eating", "健康", 1, "Proper nutrition is fundamental to health and well-being, yet dietary patterns around the world are increasingly characterized by overconsumption of processed foods and underconsumption of essential nutrients. The World Health Organization identifies unhealthy diets as one of the leading risk factors for chronic diseases globally.\n\nThe rise of ultra-processed foods, high in added sugars, unhealthy fats, and sodium, has contributed to increasing rates of obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease. These foods are engineered to be hyper-palatable, overriding natural appetite regulation mechanisms. In many countries, ultra-processed foods make up more than half of daily caloric intake.\n\nNutritional deficiencies affect billions of people worldwide. Iron deficiency anemia impacts approximately 1.8 billion people, particularly women and children in developing countries. Vitamin D deficiency is widespread in northern latitudes and among populations with limited sun exposure. Iodine deficiency remains the leading preventable cause of intellectual disability globally.\n\nDietary recommendations emphasize consuming plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats while limiting processed foods, added sugars, and excessive sodium. The Mediterranean diet, rich in plant foods, olive oil, and fish, has been consistently associated with reduced risks of chronic diseases and longer lifespans. However, healthy eating is not just about individual choices; food environments, agricultural policies, and economic factors all shape dietary patterns and must be addressed to improve population nutrition.",
"适当的营养对健康和幸福至关重要，但全球饮食模式越来越以过度消费加工食品和不足消费必需营养素为特征。世界卫生组织将不健康饮食确定为全球慢性病的主要风险因素之一。\n\n超加工食品的兴起导致了肥胖、糖尿病和心血管疾病发病率的增加。这些食品被设计成超适口的，压倒了天然的食欲调节机制。\n\n营养缺乏影响着全球数十亿人。缺铁性贫血影响约18亿人。维生素D缺乏在北纬地区和阳光照射有限的人群中很普遍。碘缺乏仍然是全球可预防的智力障碍的主要原因。\n\n饮食建议强调多吃水果、蔬菜、全谷物、瘦肉蛋白和健康脂肪，同时限制加工食品和添加糖。",
338, [["What has contributed to increasing rates of obesity and diabetes?","Eating too many vegetables","The rise of ultra-processed foods high in added sugars, unhealthy fats, and sodium","Drinking too much water","Exercising too much","B","文章指出超加工食品的兴起导致了肥胖和糖尿病发病率增加。"],["How many people does iron deficiency anemia impact?","About 180 million","About 1.8 billion","About 18 million","About 18 billion","B","文章指出缺铁性贫血影响约18亿人。"],["What diet is consistently associated with reduced risks of chronic diseases?","The fast food diet","The Mediterranean diet rich in plant foods, olive oil, and fish","The high-protein diet","The low-carb diet","B","文章指出地中海饮食与降低慢性病风险和更长寿命持续相关。"],["The word 'hyper-palatable' most likely means:","Very unappetizing","Extremely appealing and tasty, designed to override natural appetite controls","Slightly salty","Bitter and sour","B","'hyper-palatable'意为'超适口的、极其美味的'。"]]],

  [121, "The Global Obesity Epidemic", "健康", 2, "Obesity has reached epidemic proportions globally, with rates nearly tripling since 1975. The World Health Organization reports that in 2016, more than 1.9 billion adults were overweight, and of these, over 650 million were obese. This trend affects both developed and developing countries.\n\nObesity increases the risk of numerous health conditions including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, certain cancers, and musculoskeletal disorders. It reduces life expectancy by an average of three to ten years and significantly impairs quality of life. The healthcare costs associated with obesity are enormous, accounting for a significant portion of healthcare spending in many countries.\n\nThe causes of obesity are complex and multifactorial. While individual choices about diet and physical activity matter, the broader food environment plays a crucial role. The widespread availability and marketing of calorie-dense, nutrient-poor foods, combined with increasingly sedentary lifestyles, creates conditions that promote weight gain.\n\nChildhood obesity is particularly concerning as it tends to persist into adulthood and increases the risk of early-onset chronic diseases. Rates of childhood obesity have risen dramatically, with approximately 124 million children and adolescents worldwide classified as obese. Prevention efforts focus on improving school nutrition, increasing physical activity, and restricting marketing of unhealthy foods to children.",
"肥胖已达到全球流行病的程度，自1975年以来发病率几乎增加了两倍。世界卫生组织报告2016年超过19亿成年人超重，其中超过6.5亿人肥胖。\n\n肥胖增加了许多健康状况的风险，包括2型糖尿病、心血管疾病、某些癌症和肌肉骨骼疾病。它平均减少3到10年的预期寿命。\n\n肥胖的原因是复杂多因素的。虽然个人关于饮食和体力活动的选择很重要，但更广泛的食品环境起着关键作用。\n\n儿童肥胖特别令人担忧，因为它往往会持续到成年。全球约1.24亿儿童和青少年被归类为肥胖。预防工作侧重于改善学校营养、增加体育活动和限制向儿童推销不健康食品。",
338, [["By how much have obesity rates increased since 1975?","Doubled","Nearly tripled","Increased tenfold","Remained the same","B","文章指出自1975年以来肥胖率几乎增加了两倍（nearly tripled）。"],["How much does obesity reduce life expectancy on average?","One to two years","Three to ten years","Fifteen to twenty years","No reduction","B","文章指出肥胖平均减少3到10年的预期寿命。"],["How many children and adolescents worldwide are classified as obese?","About 24 million","About 124 million","About 500 million","About 1 billion","B","文章指出全球约1.24亿儿童和青少年被归类为肥胖。"],["The word 'multifactorial' most likely means:","Having a single cause","Involving multiple contributing factors","Very simple to understand","Impossible to solve","B","'multifactorial'意为'多因素的'。"]]],

  [122, "Exercise and Physical Health", "健康", 1, "Regular physical activity is one of the most important things people can do for their health. The World Health Organization recommends at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity per week for adults, yet approximately one in four adults globally fails to meet these guidelines.\n\nThe benefits of regular exercise are extensive. Physical activity reduces the risk of cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, and several cancers. It strengthens bones and muscles, improves mental health and mood, and increases chances of living longer. Even modest increases in physical activity yield significant health benefits for previously inactive individuals.\n\nSedentary behavior, characterized by prolonged sitting, has emerged as an independent health risk factor. Even people who meet recommended exercise guidelines but spend most of their remaining time sitting face increased health risks. The modern workplace, with its emphasis on desk-based work, contributes to excessive sedentary time.\n\nBarriers to physical activity include lack of time, limited access to safe exercise spaces, and the convenience of motorized transportation. Communities designed for walking and cycling, workplace wellness programs, and school physical education requirements all help create environments that support active lifestyles. Finding activities that are enjoyable and sustainable is key to maintaining regular exercise habits throughout life.",
"有规律的体育活动是人们为健康能做的最重要的事情之一。世界卫生组织建议成年人每周至少进行150分钟中等强度的有氧运动，但全球约四分之一的成年人未达到这些指南。\n\n定期运动的好处广泛。体育活动降低心血管疾病、2型糖尿病和几种癌症的风险。它增强骨骼和肌肉，改善心理健康和情绪。\n\n久坐行为已成为独立的健康风险因素。即使达到推荐运动指南但大部分剩余时间坐着的人也面临增加的健康风险。\n\n体育活动的障碍包括缺乏时间、安全运动空间有限和机动交通的便利性。找到令人愉快和可持续的活动是维持终身定期运动习惯的关键。",
338, [["What is WHO's recommended weekly exercise for adults?","At least 30 minutes total","At least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity","At least 300 minutes","At least 500 minutes","B","文章指出世卫组织建议成年人每周至少进行150分钟中等强度有氧运动。"],["What percentage of adults globally fail to meet exercise guidelines?","About one in ten","About one in four","About half","About three-quarters","B","文章指出全球约四分之一的成年人未达到运动指南。"],["What has emerged as an independent health risk factor?","Running too much","Sedentary behavior characterized by prolonged sitting","Swimming","Weight lifting","B","文章指出久坐行为已成为独立的健康风险因素。"],["The word 'sedentary' most likely means:","Very active and energetic","Characterized by sitting and little physical activity","Related to swimming","Athletic","B","'sedentary'意为'久坐的、缺乏运动的'。"]]],

  [123, "Sleep and Health", "健康", 2, "Sleep is essential for physical health, cognitive function, and emotional well-being, yet sleep deprivation has become increasingly common in modern societies. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has declared insufficient sleep a public health epidemic.\n\nAdults typically need seven to nine hours of sleep per night for optimal functioning. However, surveys indicate that approximately one-third of adults in developed countries regularly get less than seven hours. Chronic sleep deprivation impairs attention, memory, and decision-making, increasing the risk of accidents and errors.\n\nThe health consequences of inadequate sleep extend far beyond daytime fatigue. Sleep deprivation increases the risk of obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and weakened immune function. During sleep, the brain clears metabolic waste products through the glymphatic system, and insufficient sleep may contribute to the accumulation of toxic proteins associated with Alzheimer's disease.\n\nModern lifestyles contribute to poor sleep. Exposure to blue light from screens suppresses melatonin production, delaying sleep onset. Work schedules, social obligations, and the expectation of constant connectivity compete with sleep time. Caffeine and alcohol consumption can disrupt sleep architecture even when they don't prevent sleep onset.\n\nImproving sleep hygiene includes maintaining consistent sleep schedules, creating dark and cool sleeping environments, limiting screen time before bed, and avoiding caffeine in the afternoon. For those with chronic sleep disorders such as insomnia or sleep apnea, medical evaluation and treatment may be necessary.",
"睡眠对身体健康、认知功能和情感幸福至关重要，但睡眠不足在现代社会越来越普遍。美国疾病控制与预防中心宣布睡眠不足为公共健康流行病。\n\n成年人通常需要每晚7到9小时的睡眠以实现最佳功能。然而，调查显示发达国家约三分之一的成年人经常睡眠不足7小时。慢性睡眠不足损害注意力、记忆力和决策能力。\n\n睡眠不足的健康后果远远超出白天的疲劳。睡眠不足增加肥胖、糖尿病、心血管疾病和免疫功能减弱的风险。在睡眠期间，大脑通过胶质淋巴系统清除代谢废物。\n\n现代生活方式导致了不良睡眠。屏幕蓝光暴露抑制褪黑素产生。改善睡眠卫生包括保持一致的睡眠时间表、创造黑暗凉爽的睡眠环境。",
338, [["How many hours of sleep do adults typically need per night?","Five to six hours","Seven to nine hours","Ten to twelve hours","Three to four hours","B","文章指出成年人通常需要每晚7到9小时的睡眠。"],["What percentage of adults in developed countries get less than seven hours regularly?","About one-tenth","About one-third","About one-half","About two-thirds","B","文章指出发达国家约三分之一的成年人经常睡眠不足7小时。"],["What does exposure to blue light from screens do?","Improves sleep quality","Suppresses melatonin production delaying sleep onset","Has no effect on sleep","Makes you fall asleep faster","B","文章指出屏幕蓝光暴露抑制褪黑素产生，延迟睡眠开始。"],["What system clears metabolic waste from the brain during sleep?","The digestive system","The glymphatic system","The respiratory system","The muscular system","B","文章指出大脑通过胶质淋巴系统清除代谢废物。"]]],

  [124, "Stress Management", "健康", 2, "Stress has become an increasingly prevalent feature of modern life, affecting physical health, mental well-being, and overall quality of life. While some stress can be motivating, chronic stress poses serious health risks that require effective management strategies.\n\nThe body's stress response evolved to handle acute threats. When faced with danger, the fight-or-flight response releases hormones including cortisol and adrenaline, preparing the body for action. In modern life, however, stressors are often psychological and persistent rather than physical and brief, leading to chronic activation of the stress response.\n\nChronic stress contributes to numerous health problems. Elevated cortisol levels over extended periods increase the risk of cardiovascular disease, suppress immune function, promote abdominal fat storage, and impair memory and cognitive function. Stress is also linked to mental health conditions including anxiety and depression.\n\nEffective stress management involves both reducing exposure to unnecessary stressors and developing healthy coping mechanisms. Regular physical exercise reduces stress hormones and triggers endorphin release. Mindfulness meditation has been shown to reduce cortisol levels and improve emotional regulation. Social support from friends, family, and community buffers against stress effects. Time management, setting boundaries, and learning to say no reduce overwhelming commitments.\n\nWorkplace stress deserves particular attention as adults spend significant time at work. Organizations can reduce employee stress through reasonable workloads, flexible scheduling, clear expectations, and supportive management. Employee wellness programs that include stress management resources benefit both workers and organizational productivity.",
"压力已成为现代生活日益普遍的特征，影响着身体健康、心理幸福和整体生活质量。虽然一些压力可以激励人，但慢性压力带来需要有效管理策略的严重健康风险。\n\n身体的压力反应演变来处理急性威胁。当面对危险时，战斗或逃跑反应释放皮质醇和肾上腺素等激素。然而在现代生活中，压力源往往是心理性和持久性的。\n\n慢性压力导致许多健康问题。长期升高的皮质醇水平增加心血管疾病风险、抑制免疫功能、促进腹部脂肪储存和损害记忆。\n\n有效的压力管理包括减少接触不必要的压力源和发展健康的应对机制。定期体育运动会减少压力荷尔蒙。正念冥想已被证明可以降低皮质醇水平。来自朋友、家人和社区的社会支持可以缓冲压力影响。",
338, [["What hormones does the fight-or-flight response release?","Insulin and glucagon","Cortisol and adrenaline","Estrogen and testosterone","Serotonin and dopamine","B","文章指出战斗或逃跑反应释放皮质醇和肾上腺素。"],["What does chronic elevated cortisol increase the risk of?","Only headaches","Cardiovascular disease, suppressed immunity, abdominal fat, and impaired cognition","Only weight loss","Only improved memory","B","文章指出长期升高的皮质醇水平增加心血管疾病风险、抑制免疫、促进腹部脂肪和损害认知。"],["What has mindfulness meditation been shown to do?","Increase cortisol levels","Reduce cortisol levels and improve emotional regulation","Cause more stress","Only improve flexibility","B","文章指出正念冥想已被证明可以降低皮质醇水平和改善情绪调节。"],["The word 'acute' in 'acute threats' most likely means:","Mild and gradual","Severe and sudden in onset","Chronic and long-lasting","Emotional and psychological","B","'acute'在此上下文中意为'急性的、突发的'。"]]],

  [125, "Antibiotic Resistance", "健康", 3, "Antibiotic resistance has been identified by the World Health Organization as one of the biggest threats to global health, food security, and development. Bacteria that were once easily treatable with antibiotics are evolving resistance, making common infections increasingly difficult and expensive to treat.\n\nThe mechanism of resistance is natural selection in action. When antibiotics are used, susceptible bacteria die while resistant ones survive and multiply. Each course of antibiotics provides an opportunity for resistant strains to emerge and spread. The overuse and misuse of antibiotics in human medicine and agriculture accelerate this process dramatically.\n\nThe consequences of antibiotic resistance are severe. Common infections like pneumonia, tuberculosis, and urinary tract infections are becoming harder to treat. Surgical procedures and cancer treatments that rely on antibiotics to prevent infection become riskier. The World Health Organization estimates that drug-resistant infections already cause at least 700,000 deaths annually, a figure projected to reach 10 million by 2050 if current trends continue.\n\nAddressing antibiotic resistance requires coordinated global action. Healthcare providers must prescribe antibiotics only when necessary and ensure correct dosing and duration. Patients must complete prescribed courses even if they feel better. Agricultural use of antibiotics for growth promotion should be eliminated. Investment in new antibiotic development is critical, as the pipeline of new drugs has nearly dried up due to insufficient financial incentives for pharmaceutical companies. Without effective antibiotics, modern medicine as we know it would be profoundly compromised.",
"抗生素耐药性已被世界卫生组织确定为全球健康、食品安全和发展的最大威胁之一。曾经用抗生素容易治疗的细菌正在进化出耐药性，使常见感染越来越难以治疗。\n\n耐药机制是自然选择在起作用。当使用抗生素时，敏感细菌死亡而耐药细菌存活并繁殖。抗生素的过度使用和滥用大大加速了这一过程。\n\n抗生素耐药性的后果严重。常见感染如肺炎、结核病和尿路感染变得越来越难治疗。世界卫生组织估计耐药感染已经每年造成至少70万人死亡，如果当前趋势继续，到2050年预计将达到1000万人。\n\n解决抗生素耐药性需要协调的全球行动。医疗保健提供者必须只在必要时开抗生素。患者必须完成处方疗程。应该消除农业中用于促进生长的抗生素使用。",
338, [["What is the projected annual death toll from drug-resistant infections by 2050?","About 700,000","About 10 million","About 1 million","About 100 million","B","文章指出如果当前趋势继续，到2050年预计耐药感染每年将造成1000万人死亡。"],["What natural process drives antibiotic resistance?","Genetic engineering","Natural selection where resistant bacteria survive and multiply","Climate change","Vaccination","B","文章指出当使用抗生素时，敏感细菌死亡而耐药细菌存活并繁殖，这是自然选择。"],["What agricultural practice should be eliminated according to the passage?","Organic farming","Using antibiotics for growth promotion in livestock","Crop rotation","Irrigation","B","文章指出应该消除农业中用于促进生长的抗生素使用。"],["Why has the pipeline of new antibiotics nearly dried up?","Bacteria are easier to kill now","Insufficient financial incentives for pharmaceutical companies to develop new antibiotics","Too many antibiotics already exist","Antibiotics are too cheap to produce","B","文章指出由于制药公司缺乏足够的财务激励，新药研发管线几乎枯竭。"]]],

  [126, "Vaccination and Public Health", "健康", 1, "Vaccination represents one of the greatest public health achievements in human history. Vaccines have eradicated smallpox, nearly eliminated polio, and dramatically reduced the burden of diseases like measles, diphtheria, and tetanus. Despite these successes, vaccine hesitancy and access barriers threaten progress against preventable diseases.\n\nVaccines work by introducing weakened or inactive components of pathogens to stimulate the immune system without causing disease. This priming enables the body to respond rapidly and effectively if exposed to the actual pathogen in the future. Herd immunity occurs when a sufficient proportion of a population is immune, protecting those who cannot be vaccinated due to age or medical conditions.\n\nVaccine hesitancy, the reluctance or refusal to vaccinate despite availability, has been identified by the World Health Organization as a top ten global health threat. Concerns about vaccine safety, often based on debunked studies and misinformation, have led some parents to delay or refuse vaccinations for their children. Outbreaks of measles in countries where the disease was previously eliminated illustrate the real-world consequences of declining vaccination rates.\n\nGlobal vaccination coverage remains uneven. In 2019, approximately 20 million children worldwide did not receive basic vaccines, with the majority living in conflict zones and underserved rural areas. Strengthening immunization systems, improving vaccine supply chains, and building trust through community engagement are essential for extending the benefits of vaccination to all populations.",
"疫苗接种代表了人类历史上最伟大的公共卫生成就之一。疫苗已经根除了天花，几乎消灭了脊髓灰质炎，并大幅减少了麻疹、白喉和破伤风等疾病的负担。\n\n疫苗通过引入病原体的弱化或非活性成分来刺激免疫系统而不引起疾病。当足够比例的人口免疫时就会产生群体免疫，保护那些因年龄或医疗条件无法接种疫苗的人。\n\n疫苗犹豫被世界卫生组织列为全球十大健康威胁之一。对疫苗安全的担忧，通常基于已被揭穿的研究和错误信息，导致一些父母延迟或拒绝为孩子接种疫苗。\n\n全球疫苗接种覆盖率仍然不均。2019年，全球约2000万儿童未接受基本疫苗。加强免疫系统和通过社区参与建立信任至关重要。",
338, [["What disease has been eradicated through vaccination?","Polio","Measles","Smallpox","Tetanus","C","文章指出疫苗已经根除了天花。"],["What is herd immunity?","When one person is immune to all diseases","When a sufficient proportion of a population is immune, protecting those who cannot be vaccinated","When only elderly people are vaccinated","When no one is vaccinated","B","文章指出当足够比例的人口免疫时就会产生群体免疫，保护无法接种的人。"],["What has WHO identified as a top ten global health threat?","Vaccination itself","Vaccine hesitancy","Exercise","Sleep deprivation","B","文章指出疫苗犹豫被世界卫生组织列为全球十大健康威胁之一。"],["How many children worldwide did not receive basic vaccines in 2019?","About 2 million","About 20 million","About 200 million","About 200,000","B","文章指出2019年全球约2000万儿童未接受基本疫苗。"]]],

  [127, "Telemedicine and Remote Healthcare", "健康", 1, "Telemedicine, the delivery of healthcare services through digital communication technologies, has expanded dramatically in recent years. The COVID-19 pandemic accelerated adoption as both patients and providers sought alternatives to in-person visits. What was once a niche service has become a mainstream component of healthcare delivery.\n\nThe benefits of telemedicine are significant. Patients in rural or underserved areas can access specialists without traveling long distances. People with mobility limitations or chronic conditions can receive care from home. Reduced exposure to infectious diseases in waiting rooms became particularly valued during the pandemic. Telemedicine also enables more frequent monitoring of chronic conditions through remote patient monitoring devices.\n\nHowever, telemedicine faces limitations. Physical examinations are constrained, and some conditions require hands-on assessment that cannot be replicated virtually. Technology barriers, including lack of internet access and digital literacy, can exclude vulnerable populations. The inability to perform procedures, lab tests, and imaging remotely limits the scope of telemedicine services.\n\nRegulatory frameworks for telemedicine continue to evolve. Issues including licensure across state lines, insurance reimbursement parity, and privacy protections require ongoing attention. Finding the right balance between virtual and in-person care will shape the future of healthcare delivery, with many experts envisioning hybrid models that leverage the convenience of telemedicine while preserving the irreplaceable value of face-to-face medical encounters.",
"远程医疗是通过数字通信技术提供医疗服务的方式，近年来急剧扩展。新冠疫情加速了采用。曾经是小众服务的远程医疗已成为医疗保健服务的主流组成部分。\n\n远程医疗的好处是显著的。农村或服务不足地区的患者无需长途旅行就可以获得专家诊疗。行动受限或患有慢性病的人可以在家中接受护理。\n\n然而，远程医疗面临限制。体格检查受到限制，一些疾病需要无法虚拟复制的亲身体验。技术障碍可能排斥弱势群体。\n\n远程医疗的监管框架继续演变。在虚拟和面对面护理之间找到合适的平衡将塑造医疗保健的未来。许多专家设想混合模式。",
338, [["What accelerated telemedicine adoption?","Reduced internet access","The COVID-19 pandemic","Lower technology quality","Fewer doctors","B","文章指出新冠疫情加速了远程医疗的采用。"],["What is a benefit of telemedicine for rural patients?","They must travel more","They can access specialists without traveling long distances","They get worse care","They cannot use technology","B","文章指出农村患者无需长途旅行就可以获得专家诊疗。"],["What limitation of telemedicine is mentioned?","It is too expensive","Physical examinations are constrained and some conditions require hands-on assessment","It works for all medical conditions","It eliminates all in-person visits","B","文章指出体格检查受到限制，一些疾病需要亲身体验。"],["The word 'parity' in 'insurance reimbursement parity' most likely means:","Discrimination","Equality or equivalence","Superiority","Complexity","B","'parity'意为'平等、对等'。"]]],

  [128, "Substance Abuse and Addiction", "健康", 2, "Substance abuse and addiction represent significant public health challenges affecting millions of people worldwide. Addiction is a chronic, relapsing brain disease characterized by compulsive drug seeking and use despite harmful consequences. Understanding addiction as a medical condition rather than a moral failing is essential for effective treatment and policy.\n\nThe opioid crisis has drawn particular attention in recent years. In the United States, opioid overdoses claimed nearly 500,000 lives between 1999 and 2019. The crisis began with aggressive marketing of prescription painkillers, progressed to widespread misuse, and was compounded by the arrival of potent synthetic opioids like fentanyl.\n\nAddiction affects the brain's reward circuitry, particularly the dopamine system. Repeated substance use alters brain chemistry, reducing the ability to experience pleasure from natural rewards and increasing cravings for the substance. These neurological changes persist long after substance use stops, explaining the high relapse rates that characterize addiction.\n\nTreatment approaches include behavioral therapies, medication-assisted treatment, and support groups. Medication-assisted treatment combining medications like methadone or buprenorphine with counseling has been shown to be the most effective approach for opioid addiction. However, stigma surrounding medication-assisted treatment limits its availability in many communities.\n\nPrevention efforts focus on education, limiting access to prescription opioids, and addressing underlying risk factors such as trauma, mental health conditions, and social isolation. Harm reduction strategies like needle exchange programs and naloxone distribution save lives by preventing overdose deaths among those who are not yet ready for treatment.",
"药物滥用和成瘾是影响全球数百万人的重大公共健康挑战。成瘾是一种慢性、复发性的脑疾病，其特征是尽管有不良后果仍强迫性地寻找和使用药物。将成瘾理解为医学状况而非道德缺陷对于有效治疗至关重要。\n\n阿片类药物危机近年来特别引起关注。在美国，1999年至2019年间阿片类药物过量夺去了近50万人的生命。\n\n成瘾影响大脑的奖赏回路，特别是多巴胺系统。反复使用物质改变了大脑化学。\n\n治疗方法包括行为疗法、药物辅助治疗和支持小组。药物辅助治疗结合美沙酮或丁丙诺啡等药物与咨询已被证明是阿片类药物成瘾最有效的方法。\n\n预防工作侧重于教育、限制处方阿片类药物的获取和解决潜在的风险因素。",
338, [["How many lives did opioid overdoses claim in the US between 1999 and 2019?","About 50,000","About 500,000","About 5 million","About 5,000","B","文章指出1999年至2019年间美国阿片类药物过量夺去了近50万人的生命。"],["What brain system does addiction primarily affect?","The digestive system","The dopamine reward system","The respiratory system","The skeletal system","B","文章指出成瘾影响大脑的奖赏回路，特别是多巴胺系统。"],["What has been shown to be the most effective approach for opioid addiction?","Willpower alone","Medication-assisted treatment combining medications with counseling","Only support groups","Only behavioral therapy","B","文章指出药物辅助治疗结合咨询已被证明是阿片类药物成瘾最有效的方法。"],["The word 'relapsing' most likely means:","Permanently cured","Returning to a previous condition after a period of improvement","Never recurring","Getting progressively better","B","'relapsing'意为'复发的'。"]]],

  [129, "Healthy Aging", "健康", 1, "As global life expectancy continues to increase, healthy aging has become a priority for individuals and societies. The World Health Organization defines healthy aging as developing and maintaining functional ability that enables well-being in older age, rather than simply the absence of disease.\n\nSeveral factors contribute to healthy aging. Regular physical activity helps maintain muscle strength, balance, and cardiovascular health, reducing the risk of falls and chronic diseases. Cognitive engagement through learning, social interaction, and mentally stimulating activities may help preserve cognitive function. Social connections protect against loneliness and depression, which are significant risks for older adults.\n\nNutrition plays a critical role in healthy aging. Older adults often require fewer calories but more of certain nutrients including protein, calcium, vitamin D, and vitamin B12. Age-related changes in appetite and digestion can make meeting nutritional needs challenging. Malnutrition affects up to one-quarter of older adults in some populations.\n\nPreventive healthcare remains important throughout life. Regular screenings for cancer, cardiovascular disease, and other age-related conditions enable early detection and treatment. Vaccinations against influenza, pneumococcal disease, and shingles are particularly important for older adults whose immune systems may be weakened.\n\nAge-friendly environments support healthy aging by ensuring accessibility, safety, and social inclusion. Features like well-maintained sidewalks, adequate lighting, accessible public transportation, and community centers enable older adults to remain active and engaged in their communities.",
"随着全球预期寿命持续增加，健康老龄化已成为个人和社会的优先事项。世界卫生组织将健康老龄化定义为发展和维持使老年幸福的功能能力。\n\n几个因素有助于健康老龄化。定期体育活动有助于维持肌肉力量、平衡和心血管健康。通过学习、社交和智力刺激活动的认知参与可能有助于保持认知功能。社交联系防止孤独和抑郁。\n\n营养在健康老龄化中起着关键作用。老年人通常需要较少热量但更多某些营养素。营养不良在一些人群中影响多达四分之一的老年人。\n\n预防性医疗保健在整个生命中仍然重要。定期筛查使早期发现和治疗成为可能。对老年人来说，针对流感、肺炎球菌疾病和带状疱疹的疫苗接种特别重要。\n\n适老环境通过确保无障碍、安全和社会包容来支持健康老龄化。",
338, [["What does WHO define healthy aging as?","Only the absence of disease","Developing and maintaining functional ability that enables well-being in older age","Living to 100 years old","Never getting sick","B","文章指出世卫组织将健康老龄化定义为发展和维持使老年幸福的功能能力。"],["What proportion of older adults does malnutrition affect in some populations?","Up to one-tenth","Up to one-quarter","Up to one-half","Up to three-quarters","B","文章指出营养不良在一些人群中影响多达四分之一的老年人。"],["What type of engagement may help preserve cognitive function?","Only physical exercise","Cognitive engagement through learning, social interaction, and mentally stimulating activities","Only watching television","Only sleeping","B","文章指出通过学习、社交和智力刺激活动的认知参与可能有助于保持认知功能。"],["The word 'accessibility' most likely means:","The quality of being easy to approach, enter, or use","The quality of being expensive","The quality of being hidden","The quality of being new","A","'accessibility'意为'无障碍性、可及性'。"]]],

  [130, "Health Effects of Air Quality", "健康", 2, "Air quality has a profound impact on human health, with both outdoor and indoor air pollution contributing to millions of premature deaths annually. The World Health Organization estimates that air pollution causes approximately seven million deaths worldwide each year, making it the single largest environmental health risk.\n\nOutdoor air pollution stems from vehicle emissions, industrial processes, power generation, and agricultural activities. Fine particulate matter, known as PM2.5, poses the greatest health risk because these microscopic particles penetrate deep into the lungs and enter the bloodstream. Long-term exposure to PM2.5 increases the risk of heart disease, stroke, lung cancer, and respiratory infections.\n\nIndoor air pollution affects approximately three billion people who rely on solid fuels like wood, dung, and coal for cooking and heating. The resulting household air pollution causes approximately four million premature deaths annually, primarily among women and children in developing countries who have the greatest exposure.\n\nImproving air quality requires action at multiple levels. Transitioning to clean energy sources, implementing vehicle emission standards, and improving public transportation reduce outdoor pollution. Clean cooking technologies and improved ventilation address indoor air quality. Individual actions such as avoiding exercise near busy roads and using air purifiers in polluted environments can reduce personal exposure. The economic benefits of improved air quality, including reduced healthcare costs and increased productivity, far outweigh the costs of pollution control measures.",
"空气质量对人类健康有深远影响，室内外空气污染每年导致数百万人过早死亡。世界卫生组织估计空气污染每年在全球造成约700万人死亡。\n\n室外空气污染源于车辆排放、工业过程、发电和农业活动。细颗粒物（PM2.5）造成最大的健康风险。\n\n室内空气污染影响约30亿依赖固体燃料做饭和取暖的人。由此产生的家庭空气污染每年造成约400万人过早死亡，主要是在发展中国家暴露最大的妇女和儿童。\n\n改善空气质量需要多层面行动。转向清洁能源、实施车辆排放标准和改善公共交通可以减少室外污染。",
338, [["How many deaths does air pollution cause annually worldwide according to WHO?","About 1 million","About 7 million","About 70 million","About 700,000","B","文章指出世卫组织估计空气污染每年造成约700万人死亡。"],["How many people are affected by indoor air pollution from solid fuels?","About 300 million","About 3 billion","About 30 million","About 300,000","B","文章指出约30亿人依赖固体燃料受到影响。"],["What does PM2.5 refer to?","Large dust particles","Fine particulate matter that poses the greatest health risk from air pollution","A type of gas","A weather measurement","B","文章指出PM2.5是造成最大健康风险的细颗粒物。"],["How many premature deaths does household air pollution cause annually?","About 400,000","About 4 million","About 40 million","About 400","B","文章指出家庭空气污染每年造成约400万人过早死亡。"]]],

  [131, "Food Safety and Public Health", "健康", 1, "Food safety is a critical public health issue that affects everyone. The World Health Organization estimates that approximately 600 million people, nearly one in ten worldwide, fall ill after consuming contaminated food each year, and 420,000 die as a result. Children under five carry 40 percent of the foodborne disease burden.\n\nCommon foodborne pathogens include Salmonella, E. coli, Listeria, and Norovirus. These organisms can cause symptoms ranging from mild gastrointestinal discomfort to life-threatening conditions. Contamination can occur at any point in the food chain, from farm to table, making comprehensive food safety systems essential.\n\nFood safety challenges are evolving. Globalization of food supply chains means that contamination in one country can affect consumers worldwide. Climate change is altering patterns of food contamination as rising temperatures affect bacterial growth and water quality. Antimicrobial resistance in foodborne bacteria makes infections harder to treat.\n\nThe WHO promotes five keys to safer food: keep clean, separate raw and cooked food, cook thoroughly, keep food at safe temperatures, and use safe water and raw materials. Implementing these principles in both commercial and home kitchens significantly reduces the risk of foodborne illness. Strengthening food safety systems through better regulation, surveillance, and international cooperation is essential for protecting public health in an increasingly interconnected world.",
"食品安全是影响每个人的关键公共卫生问题。世界卫生组织估计每年约6亿人（全球近十分之一）因食用受污染的食物而生病，42万人因此死亡。5岁以下儿童承担40%的食源性疾病负担。\n\n常见的食源性病原体包括沙门氏菌、大肠杆菌、李斯特菌和诺如病毒。污染可能发生在从农场到餐桌的食物链的任何环节。\n\n食品安全挑战正在演变。食品供应链全球化意味着一个国家的污染可能影响全球消费者。抗菌药物耐药性使感染更难治疗。\n\n世卫组织推广更安全食品的五项要点：保持清洁、分开生熟食品、彻底煮熟、将食物保持在安全温度、使用安全的水和原材料。",
338, [["How many people fall ill from contaminated food annually worldwide?","About 60 million","About 600 million","About 6 billion","About 6 million","B","文章指出每年约6亿人因食用受污染的食物而生病。"],["What percentage of the foodborne disease burden do children under five carry?","About 10%","About 25%","About 40%","About 60%","C","文章指出5岁以下儿童承担40%的食源性疾病负担。"],["How many deaths result from contaminated food annually?","About 42,000","About 420,000","About 4.2 million","About 42 million","B","文章指出每年42万人因食用受污染食物而死亡。"],["How many keys to safer food does WHO promote?","Three","Five","Seven","Ten","B","文章指出世卫组织推广更安全食品的五项要点。"]]],

  [132, "The Importance of Hydration", "健康", 1, "Water is essential for virtually every function in the human body, making proper hydration crucial for health. The human body is approximately 60 percent water, and even mild dehydration can impair physical and cognitive performance.\n\nWater regulates body temperature, transports nutrients and oxygen to cells, lubricates joints, protects organs and tissues, and removes waste products. The body loses water continuously through breathing, sweating, and elimination, making regular fluid replacement necessary.\n\nDehydration occurs when the body loses more water than it takes in. Even mild dehydration of one to two percent of body weight can cause headaches, fatigue, decreased alertness, and reduced physical performance. Moderate dehydration can lead to dizziness, rapid heartbeat, and reduced blood pressure. Severe dehydration is a medical emergency that can cause confusion, fainting, and organ damage.\n\nIndividual hydration needs vary based on factors including body size, activity level, climate, and health conditions. While the commonly cited recommendation of eight glasses of water per day provides a general guideline, actual needs may be higher for people who exercise vigorously, live in hot climates, or are pregnant or breastfeeding. Thirst is generally a reliable indicator of hydration needs for healthy adults, though older adults may have diminished thirst sensation.\n\nWater from foods, particularly fruits and vegetables, contributes to overall hydration. Beverages including milk, tea, and coffee also count toward daily fluid intake, though caffeinated drinks may have a mild diuretic effect. Monitoring urine color provides a simple way to assess hydration status: pale yellow indicates adequate hydration while darker colors suggest the need for more fluids.",
"水对人体几乎所有功能都是必不可少的，使适当的水合对健康至关重要。人体约60%是水，即使是轻度脱水也可能损害身体和认知表现。\n\n水调节体温、将营养和氧气输送到细胞、润滑关节、保护器官和组织并清除废物。身体通过呼吸、出汗和排泄持续失水。\n\n脱水发生在身体失水多于摄入时。即使轻度脱水（体重减少1-2%）也可能导致头痛、疲劳、警觉性下降和身体表现降低。中度脱水可能导致头晕和心率加快。严重脱水是医疗紧急情况。\n\n个人水合需求因体型、活动水平、气候和健康状况等因素而异。监测尿液颜色是评估水合状态的简单方法：浅黄色表示水合充足。",
338, [["What percentage of the human body is water?","About 40%","About 60%","About 80%","About 90%","B","文章指出人体约60%是水。"],["What can even mild dehydration of 1-2% of body weight cause?","No noticeable effects","Headaches, fatigue, decreased alertness, and reduced physical performance","Only increased thirst","Weight gain","B","文章指出轻度脱水可导致头痛、疲劳、警觉性下降和身体表现降低。"],["What provides a simple way to assess hydration status?","Body weight","Monitoring urine color","Blood pressure","Heart rate","B","文章指出监测尿液颜色是评估水合状态的简单方法。"],["What urine color indicates adequate hydration?","Dark brown","Bright red","Pale yellow","Colorless","C","文章指出浅黄色尿液表示水合充足。"]]],

  [133, "Health Benefits of Social Connection", "健康", 2, "Social connections are increasingly recognized as a fundamental determinant of health and longevity. Research consistently demonstrates that people with strong social relationships live longer, experience fewer health problems, and report higher levels of well-being than those who are socially isolated.\n\nA landmark meta-analysis found that the effect of social isolation on mortality risk is comparable to smoking fifteen cigarettes per day and exceeds the effects of obesity and physical inactivity. Socially isolated individuals face approximately a 50 percent increased risk of premature death from all causes.\n\nThe mechanisms through which social connections affect health are multiple. Social support provides practical assistance during illness, emotional comfort during stress, and encouragement for healthy behaviors. Social interaction stimulates cognitive function and may protect against dementia. Belonging to social groups provides a sense of meaning and identity that promotes psychological resilience.\n\nConversely, loneliness and social isolation are associated with increased inflammation, weakened immune function, elevated blood pressure, and higher rates of depression and anxiety. The stress of chronic loneliness activates the body's threat response systems, contributing to wear and tear on cardiovascular and immune systems over time.\n\nModern society presents challenges to maintaining social connections. Geographic mobility separates families, digital communication sometimes replaces face-to-face interaction, and demanding work schedules limit time for relationships. Deliberate efforts to maintain and strengthen social ties through community involvement, regular contact with friends and family, and participation in group activities are essential investments in long-term health.",
"社会联系越来越被认为是健康和长寿的基本决定因素。研究一致表明，拥有强大社会关系的人比社会孤立的人活得更长、健康问题更少。\n\n一项具有里程碑意义的荟萃分析发现，社会隔离对死亡风险的影响相当于每天吸15支烟，超过了肥胖和缺乏运动的影响。社会隔离的个体面临约50%的过早死亡增加风险。\n\n社会联系影响健康的机制是多方面的。社交互动刺激认知功能，可能预防痴呆。\n\n相反，孤独和社会隔离与炎症增加、免疫功能减弱、血压升高以及抑郁和焦虑率更高有关。\n\n现代社会对维持社会联系提出了挑战。通过社区参与、与朋友和家人定期联系和参加群体活动来有意识地维护和加强社会联系是对长期健康的重要投资。",
338, [["What is the effect of social isolation on mortality risk comparable to?","Exercising daily","Smoking fifteen cigarettes per day","Eating vegetables","Sleeping eight hours","B","文章指出社会隔离对死亡风险的影响相当于每天吸15支烟。"],["What increased risk of premature death do socially isolated individuals face?","About 10%","About 25%","About 50%","About 100%","C","文章指出社会隔离的个体面临约50%的过早死亡增加风险。"],["What does chronic loneliness activate in the body?","The digestive system","The body's threat response systems contributing to wear on cardiovascular and immune systems","The growth system","The reproductive system","B","文章指出慢性孤独激活身体的威胁反应系统。"],["The word 'meta-analysis' most likely means:","A single study","A statistical analysis combining results from multiple studies","A laboratory experiment","A survey of one person","B","'meta-analysis'意为'荟萃分析'，是综合多项研究结果的统计分析。"]]],

  [134, "Preventive Healthcare", "健康", 1, "Preventive healthcare focuses on preventing illnesses and conditions before they occur, rather than treating them after symptoms appear. This approach offers significant benefits for both individual health and healthcare system sustainability.\n\nPrimary prevention aims to prevent disease before it occurs through measures such as vaccination, health education, and lifestyle modification. Secondary prevention involves early detection and treatment of disease through screening programs. Tertiary prevention focuses on managing existing diseases to prevent complications and improve quality of life.\n\nRoutine health screenings are a cornerstone of preventive care. Blood pressure checks, cholesterol tests, cancer screenings, and diabetes assessments can detect conditions early when they are most treatable. Despite the proven benefits, many people skip recommended screenings due to lack of awareness, cost concerns, or fear of bad news.\n\nLifestyle modifications are among the most effective preventive measures. Regular exercise, balanced nutrition, adequate sleep, stress management, and avoiding tobacco and excessive alcohol significantly reduce the risk of chronic diseases. Studies suggest that healthy lifestyle behaviors could prevent up to 80 percent of heart disease and stroke cases and approximately 40 percent of cancer cases.\n\nThe economic case for preventive healthcare is compelling. Preventing chronic diseases costs far less than treating them. Every dollar invested in vaccination programs saves multiple dollars in treatment costs. Workplace wellness programs that promote preventive behaviors reduce absenteeism and healthcare spending while improving productivity.",
"预防性医疗保健侧重于在疾病发生之前进行预防，而不是在症状出现后治疗。这种方法对个人健康和医疗系统的可持续性都提供了显著好处。\n\n一级预防旨在通过疫苗接种、健康教育和生活方式改变等措施在疾病发生之前预防。二级预防涉及通过筛查程序进行早期发现和治疗。三级预防侧重于管理现有疾病以预防并发症。\n\n常规健康筛查是预防性护理的基石。血压检查、胆固醇测试、癌症筛查和糖尿病评估可以在最可治疗的早期阶段发现疾病。\n\n生活方式改变是最有效的预防措施之一。研究表明健康生活方式行为可以预防高达80%的心脏病和中风病例以及约40%的癌症病例。\n\n预防性医疗保健的经济论据令人信服。预防慢性疾病的成本远低于治疗。",
338, [["What percentage of heart disease and stroke cases could healthy lifestyle behaviors prevent?","About 20%","About 40%","About 60%","About 80%","D","文章指出健康生活方式可以预防高达80%的心脏病和中风病例。"],["What does secondary prevention involve?","Preventing disease before it occurs","Early detection and treatment of disease through screening programs","Managing complications of existing diseases","Emergency care","B","文章指出二级预防涉及通过筛查程序进行早期发现和治疗。"],["What percentage of cancer cases could healthy behaviors prevent?","About 10%","About 40%","About 60%","About 90%","B","文章指出健康生活方式可以预防约40%的癌症病例。"],["The word 'compelling' most likely means:","Weak and unconvincing","Highly convincing and difficult to argue against","Confusing and unclear","Irrelevant","B","'compelling'意为'令人信服的、有说服力的'。"]]],

  [135, "The Impact of Screen Time on Children's Health", "健康", 2, "The dramatic increase in children's screen time has raised significant concerns among parents, educators, and health professionals. With the proliferation of smartphones, tablets, and computers, children are spending more time than ever in front of screens, with potential consequences for physical and mental health.\n\nThe American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that children under 18 months avoid screen media entirely, children aged 2 to 5 limit screen use to one hour per day, and older children have consistent limits on screen time. However, surveys indicate that many children significantly exceed these recommendations.\n\nPhysical health impacts include increased risk of obesity due to sedentary behavior, disrupted sleep patterns from blue light exposure, and potential effects on vision development. The displacement of physical activity by screen time contributes to a range of health issues. Poor posture during device use can lead to musculoskeletal problems.\n\nMental and developmental concerns are equally important. Excessive screen time may impair attention span, reduce face-to-face social interaction skills, and displace time that could be spent on creative play and learning. Some research links heavy social media use among adolescents to increased rates of anxiety and depression.\n\nHowever, not all screen time is equal. Educational content, creative applications, and video communication with family members can provide positive experiences. The key is quality over quantity. Parents can promote healthy screen habits by modeling balanced technology use, creating screen-free zones and times, and actively engaging with children during media consumption rather than using screens as babysitters.",
"儿童屏幕时间的急剧增加引起了家长、教育工作者和健康专业人员的重大担忧。\n\n美国儿科学会建议18个月以下儿童完全避免屏幕媒体，2至5岁儿童将屏幕使用限制在每天1小时，较大儿童有一致的屏幕时间限制。然而调查显示许多儿童显著超过这些建议。\n\n身体健康影响包括因久坐行为增加肥胖风险、蓝光暴露导致睡眠模式破坏以及对视力发育的潜在影响。\n\n心理和发展方面的担忧同样重要。过度屏幕时间可能损害注意力持续时间、减少面对面社交互动技能。\n\n然而并非所有屏幕时间都一样。教育内容、创意应用和与家人的视频通讯可以提供积极体验。关键是质量而非数量。",
338, [["What does the American Academy of Pediatrics recommend for children under 18 months regarding screen media?","One hour per day","Avoid screen media entirely","Two hours per day","No restrictions","B","文章指出18个月以下儿童应完全避免屏幕媒体。"],["What is the recommended screen time limit for children aged 2 to 5?","30 minutes per day","One hour per day","Two hours per day","No limit","B","文章指出2至5岁儿童屏幕使用应限制在每天1小时。"],["What physical health impact of excessive screen time is mentioned?","Increased risk of obesity due to sedentary behavior","Improved eyesight","Better posture","Stronger muscles","A","文章指出因久坐行为增加肥胖风险。"],["What is the key principle regarding children's screen time?","Quantity over quality","Quality over quantity","No limits are needed","All screen time is bad","B","文章指出关键是质量而非数量。"]]],

  [136, "Healthcare Access and Disparities", "健康", 2, "Access to healthcare varies dramatically across and within countries, creating significant disparities in health outcomes. While some populations enjoy comprehensive medical services, others face barriers that prevent them from receiving even basic care, reflecting deep-seated social and economic inequalities.\n\nFinancial barriers are among the most significant obstacles to healthcare access. In countries without universal healthcare coverage, medical expenses can be catastrophic for low-income families. Even in countries with public healthcare systems, out-of-pocket costs for medications and services can deter people from seeking necessary care.\n\nGeographic barriers disproportionately affect rural populations. Rural areas often lack hospitals, specialists, and advanced medical equipment. Residents may need to travel long distances for care, creating burdens of time and expense that discourage regular check-ups and timely treatment of health issues.\n\nCultural and linguistic barriers affect minority and immigrant communities. Patients who cannot communicate effectively with healthcare providers may receive suboptimal care. Cultural beliefs about illness and treatment may conflict with medical recommendations, leading to non-adherence or avoidance of care.\n\nSystemic discrimination in healthcare contributes to disparities in treatment and outcomes. Studies document that racial and ethnic minorities often receive lower quality care even when controlling for insurance status and income. Implicit bias among healthcare providers can affect clinical decision-making. Addressing healthcare disparities requires comprehensive strategies including expanding insurance coverage, increasing provider diversity, improving cultural competency training, and investing in underserved communities.",
"获取医疗保健在各国和各国内差异巨大，造成了健康结果的显著差异。一些人群享有全面医疗服务，而另一些人则面临阻碍他们接受基本护理的障碍。\n\n经济障碍是最重要的医疗保健获取障碍之一。在没有全民医疗覆盖的国家，医疗费用对低收入家庭可能是灾难性的。\n\n地理障碍对农村人口影响尤其严重。农村地区往往缺乏医院、专科医生和先进医疗设备。居民可能需要长途旅行才能就医。\n\n文化和语言障碍影响少数族裔和移民社区。无法与医疗保健提供者有效沟通的患者可能接受不理想的护理。\n\n医疗保健中的系统性歧视导致治疗和结果的差异。研究表明种族和少数民族通常接受较低质量的护理。",
338, [["What is one of the most significant obstacles to healthcare access?","Too many doctors","Financial barriers, especially in countries without universal coverage","Too many hospitals","Free healthcare everywhere","B","文章指出经济障碍是最重要的医疗保健获取障碍之一。"],["How do geographic barriers affect rural populations?","Rural areas have too many hospitals","Rural areas lack hospitals, specialists, and advanced equipment requiring long travel for care","Rural areas have better healthcare","Geography has no effect on healthcare","B","文章指出农村地区缺乏医院、专科医生和先进设备，需要长途旅行就医。"],["What does implicit bias among healthcare providers affect?","Only hospital administration","Clinical decision-making that may lead to lower quality care for minorities","Only patient satisfaction surveys","Only billing procedures","B","文章指出医疗保健提供者的隐性偏见可能影响临床决策。"],["The word 'suboptimal' most likely means:","The best possible","Less than optimal or ideal","Perfect","Average","B","'suboptimal'意为'次优的、不够理想的'。"]]]
];
